<validation>
1. Demonstrate CSWSH by connecting from attacker-controlled origin.
2. Show successful message injection or manipulation.
3. Prove IDOR by accessing other users' data via WebSocket.
4. Document authentication bypass or weakness.
5. Provide reproducible exploit code (HTML/JavaScript).
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Proper Origin header validation on server
- Token-based authentication with proper validation
- Message-level authorization checks
- Rate limiting preventing DoS
- SameSite=Strict cookies blocking CSWSH
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Session hijacking through CSWSH
- Real-time data theft (messages, notifications)
- Unauthorized actions on victim's behalf
- Account takeover via session manipulation
- Denial of service through connection flooding
- Cross-site scripting via WebSocket message reflection
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. WebSocket connections don't have CORS; always test origin validation.
2. Check if cookies are sent with WebSocket connections (CSWSH risk).
3. Test authentication state changes mid-connection.
4. Monitor for sensitive data in WebSocket messages.
5. Test IDOR by manipulating user/channel IDs in messages.
6. Use browser DevTools WS filter for message inspection.
7. Test with sandboxed iframe (null origin) for origin bypass.
8. Check for rate limiting on message and connection rates.
9. Test subscription to channels belonging to other users.
10. Look for command injection in message handlers.
</pro_tips>

<remember>WebSocket security differs fundamentally from HTTP. The same-origin policy doesn't protect WebSocket connections by default. Servers must explicitly validate the Origin header, implement proper authentication, and enforce authorization on every message. Treat every WebSocket message as potentially malicious user input.</remember>
</websocket_security_guide>
